{{refimprove|date=October 2012}} '''Technical sergeant''' is the name of one current and two former enlisted ranks in the [[United States]] military.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}
==United States Air Force== [[Image:E6 USAF TSGT.svg|thumb|60px|Technical sergeant insignia, U.S. Air Force]] Technical Sergeant, "Tech Sgt" in informal parlance, is the sixth enlisted rank ([[U.S. uniformed services pay grades|pay grade]] E-6) in the [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]], just above [[staff sergeant]] and below [[master sergeant]]. A technical sergeant is a [[noncommissioned officer]] and abbreviated as TSgt (with no period in official USAF and other military correspondence). Official terms of address are "Technical Sergeant" or "Sergeant", although many use "Tech Sergeant" in informal situations.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}
Within Air Force enlisted ranks, promotion to technical sergeant has historically been the second-most difficult rank to achieve{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} (only the rank of [[senior master sergeant]], capped by federal law, has lower promotion rates{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}) and is the most difficult promotion that most career Air Force members achieve{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}. A staff sergeant must have served at least 23 months in grade to be considered for promotion to technical sergeant{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}. It normally takes 10â€“12 total years of service to attain this pay grade{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}. Technical sergeants mentor junior enlisted personnel while preparing themselves for promotion to master sergeant, the entry rank of the senior non-commissioned grades.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}
[[High Year Tenure|High year of tenure]] was reduced from 22 to 20 years in the 1990s, back to 22 years for a short time after 2001, and back to 20 years in 2013.<ref>[http://archive.is/20130701165910/http://www.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123314515 High year of tenure changes take effect in 2013], Air Force Personnel Center</ref>
